# /expression-synth — Family P — Avatar & Embodiment

You are running the `/expression-synth` skill. This designs the **facial expression
synthesis surface**: how the avatar's face moves to reflect emotion, intent, and
conversational beats — not lip-sync (that's `/lip-sync`), not gesture (that's
`/gesture-synth`).

Discrete-emotion models (Ekman's "Big 6") miss subtlety. Continuous valence-arousal
misses intent. FACS action units capture composition but say nothing about timing.
The right surface combines all three plus conversational-beat cues (turn-taking,
back-channels, agreement nods) and intent-driven micro-expressions (curiosity, doubt,
recognition).

You are NOT an expression-model trainer. You design the control surface, pick the
regressor model, write the training-data augmentation plan, and hand off. Do not
train. Do not download checkpoints.

Expression models are mature-ish: EMOCA (2022), DECA (2020), FACSHuman (2020-current),
FLAME-based regressors. Pin checkpoints by version. If user wants absolute latest,
run `/discover --domain expression` first.

---

## When to use

- Avatar architecture is set (via `/avatar-design`) and the face rig supports
  per-vertex deformation or blendshapes (FLAME / 3DMM / Gaussian Splat w/
  blendshape head).
- Existing avatar has the right mouth but a dead face — eyes don't track,
  brows don't move, no recognition signal mid-conversation.
- Trust-calibration matters (`/agent-ux-review` flagged that the avatar should
  express uncertainty when its underlying model is uncertain).
- Multi-cultural emotion deployment — discrete-emotion mapping fails across
  cultures.

Do NOT use for:
- Whole avatar architecture → use `/avatar-design`.
- Lip-sync / mouth movement → use `/lip-sync`.
- Body gestures → use `/gesture-synth`.
- Sign-language non-manual features → use `/avatar-sign` (sign NMFs are
  grammatical, not emotional).
- Pure 2D portrait avatars without blendshapes → this skill needs a rig.

